{
  "answer": "Several works in the Falsafa corpus, primarily poetry, engage explicitly with the sounds or songs of birds, often using them as metaphors for lament, joy, exile, or the soul's expression. The most direct references appear in Allama Iqbal's *Bang-E-Dara* collections and the *Old English Elegies*. Below are key examples:\n\n- **Bang-E-Dara Part 1** (Allama Iqbal): Describes \"songs of birds came echoing from the sky\" in a pastoral scene,[^1] and declares that \"The soul-bird must not sing its anthem of the free\" while critiquing a garden unworthy of such \"songs.\"[^2]\n- **Bang-E-Dara Part 3** (Allama Iqbal): Evokes \"songbirds\" that \"wake to hear the cuckoo's call to sing,\" blending their melody with dawn's lyre;[^3] in *Shikwa*, it laments that \"The songbirds have all flown away,\" leaving one \"nightingale... still lost within its song\" full of \"sweet melodies.\"[^4]\n- **Old English Elegies**: The Wanderer-poem notes the \"cuckoo calls... with its mournful cry, summer's warden sings,\" linking the bird's sound to sorrow and exile.[^5]\n- **Diwan-E-Ghalib** (Mirza Ghalib): Metaphorically contrasts the poet's cry with \"no captive songbird's cry,\" emphasizing the bird's vocal nature.[^6]\n\nMetaphorical uses of nightingales (*bulbul*) implying song (e.g., their \"lament\" or \"melody\") are common in Iqbal's poetry across parts, but the above are the most explicit. Legal or didactic texts like the *Smṛtis* mention birds but not their vocalizations.[^7] No other works in the corpus address this topic as directly.\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, [\"Ek_Gaye_aur_Bakri\"](https://falsafa.corpus/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/22-ek-gaye-aur-bakri/translation/#p-373abc).\n\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, [\"Laaon woh tinke kahin se aashiyane ke liye\"](https://falsafa.corpus/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/08-laaon-woh-tinke-kahin-se-aashiyane-ke-liye/translation/#p-c4ec62).\n\n[^3]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, [\"Namood-e-Subah\"](https://falsafa.corpus/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/14-namood-e-subah/translation/#p-f1e75c).\n\n[^4]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, [\"Shikwa\"](https://falsafa.corpus/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/20-shikwa/translation/#p-9844a5).\n\n[^5]: *Old English Elegies*, [\"Maey ich be me sylfum soth-yied wrekan, sithas seyan, hu ich yeswinkdagum\"](https://falsafa.corpus/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/05-maey-ich-be-me-sylfum-soth-yied-wrekan-sithas-seya/translation/#p-f52e2e).\n\n[^6]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [\"Deewangi se dosh pe zunnar bhi nahin\"](https://falsafa.corpus/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/28-deewangi-se-dosh-pe-zunnar-bhi-nahin/translation/#p-c31d86).\n\n[^7]: E.g., *Āṅgirasa Smṛti* 1 (listing birds without sonic reference): [Chapter 1](https://falsafa.corpus/works/unknown-angirasa-smrti-2bf9d1/01/translation/#p-202e66).",
